{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:48:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13849"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.81,0.07,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48986"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6466"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"2394"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12797"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48986"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe pain in the perianal region, worse when sitting. He reports feeling feverish but denies any change in bowel habits. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable with a temperature of 38.2\u00b0C. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, and respiratory rate 18/min. Examination of the perianal region reveals a tender, erythematous, fluctuant swelling along most of the right side of the anal verge (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral antibiotics","Incision and drainage","Sitz baths and analgesics","MRI pelvis","Haemorrhoidectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and examination findings are consistent with an ischiorectal abscess. The most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E under local anaesthesia. This procedure is typically performed in the emergency department or operating room, depending on the size and complexity of the abscess. Surgical drainage is essential to relieve pain, prevent further spread of infection, and promote healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E only are insufficient for treating an ischiorectal abscess. While antibiotics may be used as an adjunct to surgical drainage, they cannot adequately treat the abscess on their own due to poor penetration into the abscess cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESitz baths and analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E may provide symptomatic relief but do not address the underlying problem. These measures are often recommended as supportive care after drainage has been performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the first step in management. While imaging studies can be helpful in complex cases or when there is suspicion of a fistula, they are not routinely required for straightforward ischiorectal abscesses that can be diagnosed clinically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst haemorrhoids can present as tender swellings seen at the anal verge, this patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are not consistent with haemorrhoids, and performing a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ischiorectal abscesses typically require surgical drainage as the primary treatment.","Antibiotics alone are usually insufficient for treating ischiorectal abscesses.","Imaging studies like CT or MRI may be necessary to assess the extent of the abscess and rule out fistulas in complex cases"],"references":["Sarofim M, Ooi K. Reviewing perianal abscess management and recurrence: lessons from a trainee perspective. ANZ Journal of Surgery. 2022;92(7-8):1781-1783. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/ans.17750","Sigmon DF, Emmanuel B, Tuma F. Perianal Abscess.. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459167/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20796"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20796"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jnwBsIsdtZtTS8hFXHx8ckgAczgXAT.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jnwBsIsdtZtTS8hFXHx8ckgAczgXAT.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-21T17:00:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:19:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6466"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48986"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","s